author: Mimi Morley
time required: 1 hour
---

Fill and boil your kettle. Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto a #baking tray{} (to completely cover the bottom) and pop in your oven. Peel the @potatoes{450}, chop them into 3cm chunks. Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onions{2}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Thinly slice the @Portobello mushrooms{3}(thinly sliced), peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on the @plain flour{8%tsp}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season the potatoes with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}, turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a saucepan over medium heat, add the red onion and season with @salt{}. Cook, stirring regularly until soft, ~{8-10%minutes}. Meanwhile, drizzle @oil{} in a #frying pan{} over high heat and add the mushrooms. Cook, stirring, until golden, ~{6-8%minutes}. Stir the garlic into the mushrooms, season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}, then remove from the heat.

> TIP: Add a splash of oil to the pan if it's needed.

Once the onions are soft, add half the @balsamic vinegar{24%ml} and cook for a further ~{1%minute} until evaporated then remove from the heat.

Slice the @French Camembert{125%g} so you have roughly 2 long slices per person (see ingredients for amount you need). Cut the @puff pastry sheet{1} in half widthways to make rectangles - you want half a sheet of pastry per person. Divide the balsamic onion onto the bottom half of each pastry rectangle. Top this with the mushrooms then add the slices of camembert. Dampen the pastry edges with some @water{150%ml} then fold the top half of the pastry over the filling to enclose, gently press down the edges of the pastry with the back of a #fork{} to seal the parcel on all 3 sides.

Use a sharp #knife{} to gently score 3 diagonal lines on the top of the pastry lid. Carefully transfer the pastry parcels to a large baking tray (or two). Move the potatoes to the middle shelf of your oven and pop the wellingtons onto the top shelf of your oven to bake until the pastry is golden, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Wipe out the saucepan you used for the onions. Pop the pan on medium heat and add a drizzle of @oil{} and the shallot. Fry until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the remaining balsamic vinegar and allow to evaporate, ~{1%minute}. Add the @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @redcurrant jelly{25%g} and @water{150%ml}, bring to a boil then lower the heat and simmer until glossy and slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Once glossy, remove from the heat.

Pop your #mushroom frying pan{} back on medium high heat (no need to wash) and add a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the @tenderstem broccoli{150%g} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Fry until starting to colour, ~{2-3%minutes} then add a splash of @water{}. Cover with a #lid{} or some #tin foil{} and allow to steam fry until tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Reheat the sauce if necessary. Divide the wellingtons between plates and serve the potatoes and broccoli next to them with the sauce drizzled over it. Enjoy!